## One Week In

Seven days into this challenge and today felt like one of the most important so far. HIPAA is one of those terms I had heard constantly before starting this project — but I realized pretty quickly that hearing a term and actually understanding what it requires are very different things. Today I sat down and tried to genuinely understand what HIPAA means, what it demands, and why it exists in the first place.

---

## What I Worked On Today

HIPAA — the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act — is the US law that governs how healthcare organizations must protect patient health information. For this project, the most relevant part is the **HIPAA Security Rule**, which specifically covers **electronic protected health information (ePHI)** — the kind of data an OpenMRS system handles every day.

The Security Rule organizes its requirements into three categories of safeguards. When I first read through them I thought it was an odd way to structure a law — but the more I sat with it, the more the logic made sense. Risk does not come from just one direction. It comes from people, from physical environments, and from technology — and HIPAA addresses all three.

**Administrative Safeguards** are about leadership, process, and people. Things like conducting regular risk assessments, assigning a security officer, training staff on how to handle patient data, and having documented policies that people actually follow. This category deals with human error, insider threats, and organizational accountability.

**Physical Safeguards** are about the physical environment where ePHI lives. Workstations that access OpenMRS should lock when unattended. Server rooms should have controlled access. Backup media should be stored securely. For a cloud deployment on AWS, a lot of the physical security is inherited from AWS data centers — but that does not mean physical safeguards disappear entirely. Endpoints still matter.

**Technical Safeguards** are the technology controls — encryption, access controls, audit logging, secure transmission. This is often where technical teams spend most of their energy, and for good reason. But what I keep learning throughout this challenge is that technical controls alone are never enough. If the administrative and physical layers are weak, even the best technical controls can be undermined.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

Something that clicked today is that HIPAA deliberately uses the phrase **"reasonable and appropriate"** when describing what organizations must do. That phrase appears throughout the Security Rule and it means that HIPAA is not a one-size-fits-all checklist. A small rural clinic running OpenMRS with three staff members has different resources and risks than a large hospital network. HIPAA acknowledges that and asks organizations to implement safeguards that make sense for their specific situation.

That was more nuanced than I expected from a federal law. It also means that "we could not afford it" is not automatically an excuse — organizations are expected to document their reasoning when they choose not to implement a particular control. That documentation is itself a compliance requirement.

The three-category structure also clicked for me when I connected it back to Day 5. Governance, risk, and compliance working together — and here it shows up again inside HIPAA itself. Administrative safeguards are essentially governance. Technical safeguards are risk controls. And the whole framework exists to drive compliance. The same logic keeps appearing at different levels of the field.

