## Applying This to OpenMRS on AWS

Thinking through what HIPAA safeguards would look like for a real OpenMRS deployment, here is how I mapped the three categories:

**Administrative:**
- Assign a named Security Officer responsible for HIPAA compliance
- Conduct and document a formal risk assessment of the OpenMRS environment
- Establish a process for regular review of who has access to patient data and why
- Train all staff who interact with OpenMRS on their HIPAA responsibilities

**Physical:**
- Ensure workstations accessing OpenMRS automatically lock after a period of inactivity
- Control physical access to any on-premises infrastructure
- For AWS-hosted components — review AWS's physical security certifications and understand the shared responsibility model

**Technical:**
- Enforce HTTPS for all OpenMRS web access — no unencrypted transmission of ePHI
- Encrypt the OpenMRS database at rest
- Implement role-based access controls so users only see the data they need for their job
- Enable audit logging to track who accessed what and when
- Require MFA for all administrative accounts

Going through that exercise made HIPAA feel much more concrete than reading the regulation alone. These are real decisions that real OpenMRS administrators have to make.

