## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the **2019 UConn Health data breach** — a phishing attack that gave attackers access to employee email accounts containing patient information, affecting over 326,000 people. UConn Health faced a HHS investigation and significant reputational damage.

What stood out to me was that this breach was fundamentally an administrative safeguards failure. The technical controls on the email system were not enough to compensate for insufficient staff training on phishing awareness — which falls squarely in the administrative category. The attackers did not break through a firewall. They got an employee to hand over their credentials.

I keep coming back to this pattern across multiple days now: technical controls matter, but they do not operate in a vacuum. The human layer — which is what administrative safeguards are designed to address — is consistently where breaches find their entry point. HIPAA understood that when it was written, which is why all three categories carry equal weight.

